<statement>
<p>Solve this system of equations using elimination.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{7}{x}-{5}{y}=-{14}</m> </p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle-{8}{x}+{6}{y}={18}</m></p>
<p><input type="text" style="width:10.6ch" name="qn0" id="qn0" value="" autocomplete="off" aria-label="Question 1" class="text"/></p>

</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li><m>\displaystyle{\left({3},{7}\right)}</m></li></ul></p><p>We chose (for no special reason) to use the first equation to eliminate x from the second equation.</p>
<p>To eliminate we need the scaled version of equation one to have a coefficient of --8. So we scale by <m>\displaystyle--\frac{{8}}{{7}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-\frac{{-{8}}}{{7}}{\left({7}{x}+-{5}{y}\right)}=-\frac{{-{8}}}{{7}}{\left(-{14}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{\left(-{8}\right)}{x}+-{5.7142857142857}{y}=-{16}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{8}{x}+{6}{y}={18}</m></p>
<p>Adding these two equations gives us</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{0.28571428571429}{y}={2}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}=\frac{{2}}{{0.28571428571429}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}={7}</m></p>
<p>Finally we can substitute this y value into the first equation to solve for x.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{7}{x}+-{5}{\left({7}\right)}=-{14}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{7}{x}+{\left(-{35}\right)}=-{14}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{7}{x}=-{14}-{\left(-{35}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{7}{x}={21}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}=\frac{{21}}{{7}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}={3}</m></p>
<p>Thus the answer is <m>\displaystyle{\left({3},{7}\right)}</m>.</p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>